k-NN¶

  • Start with training data.
  • Given a new data point $x$ compute its distance to each training data point.
  • Select $k$ nearest neighbors of $x$ in the training data and check their labels.
  • The label which appears most often is assigned to the point $x$ (decide what to do with ties).

Distance:

  • Euclidean
  • $L_p$ (in particular $L_1$)
  • No need to compute roots while working with $L_p$ distances.
  • Split images and labels into a training data set and test data set.
  • Use about 10,000 numbers for training (the code may run slow if there will be too many), about 500-1000 for testing.

From the course website:

In [169]:
%config InlineBackend.figure_format = 'retina'
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.colors import ListedColormap, Normalize


def plot_clusters(X, y, p=None, p_label=None, neighbors=None):
    """
    Plots nearest neighbors of a given point.

    X:
        A 2-dimensional numpy array with coordinates
        of points in clusters
    y:
        A 1-dimensional numpy array with labels of points
    p:
        An array with coordinates of the point whose
        neighbors will be plotted.
    p_label:
        The predicted label of the point p.
    neighbors:
        A list of row numbers of X which are the nearest
        neighbors of the point p.
    """

    # build a custom colormap
    col_list = ['dodgerblue', 'limegreen', 'red', 'orange', 'fuchsia']
    colors = ListedColormap(col_list)
    norm = Normalize(0, len(col_list))

    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
    with plt.style.context('seaborn'):
        scatter = plt.scatter(X[:, 0],
                              X[:, 1],
                              c=y,
                              s=90,
                              cmap=colors,
                              norm=norm,
                              label=y)
        if p is not None:
            p_col = "k" if p_label is None else colors(norm(p_label))
            plt.plot(p[0], p[1], marker="*", mfc=p_col, mec="k", ms=30, mew=2)
        if neighbors is not None:
            plt.scatter(X[neighbors, 0],
                        X[neighbors, 1],
                        edgecolors='black',
                        linewidth=3,
                        facecolors="None",
                        s=300)
        plt.legend(*scatter.legend_elements(),
                   markerscale=1.5,
                   prop={
                       "size": 12,
                       "weight": "normal"
                   })
    plt.show()

Training and test data¶

Permute images and their labels:

In [172]:

Out[172]:
array([2, 0, 7, 6, 9, 5, 3, 4, 8, 1])
In [173]:
# permute data
rng = np.random.default_rng(2)
reorder = rng.permutation(len(images))
images = images[reorder]
labels = labels[reorder]

Then we can select training and test data:

In [174]:
train_num = 10000
test_num = 1000

train_images = images[:train_num]
train_labels = labels[:train_num]

test_images = images[train_num: train_num + test_num]
test_labels = labels[train_num: train_num + test_num]

Confusion matrix¶

Useful for representing accuracy of prediction. Rows correspond to actual labels, columns to the predicted labels. The value in a given row and column shows how many data points with the actual label corresponding to the row were predicted to have the label corresponding to the column.
